{"/service/ndnp/mb/batch_mb_basil_ver01/data/sn83020847/00517170835/1945100401/0553.xml":{"full_text":"NATIONAL\nTruman Breaks Precedent\nBy Visiting Supreme Court\nAttends Opening Session to See Harold Burton, His\nAppointee, Sworn In\nWashington, Oct. I\u2014(AP)\u2014.Presi\ndent Truman today broke a 155-year\nold precedent, by visiting the Supreme\nCourt as it formally opened its 1945-\n46 term.\nHe made the surprise visit to wit\nness the swearing in of his first\nnominee to the high tribunal, Harold\nH. Burton of Ohio, and the formal\nintroduction to the court of Atty-Gen\nTom Clark of Texas, also his ap\npointee.\nAfter a brief session, Chief Justice\nHarlan F. Stone recessed the court\nuntil Monday, when it will tackle a\ndocket already crowded with major\ncases and expected to grow as recon\nversion progresses.\nCourt attaches said Mr Truman's\nvisit wa3 the first made by a Presi\ndent in the tribunal\u2019s 155-year history.\nWearing a gray business suit, he\nslipped quietly into the courtroom\nthrough a side entrance seven min\nutes before the session opened at\nnoon. Court Marsha! Thomas E.\nWaggaman preceded him and bade\nIbe audience rise.\nMr Truman shook hands with\nClark, and then sat at a counsel table\ndirectly beneath the bench. When\nthe justices filed into the chamber,\nbe rose with the rest of the audience.\nCourt Crier John A. Kenning then\nintoned the traditional \"Oyez! Oycz.\u201d\nofficially opening a new eight-month\nteim.\nBurton, 57-year-old former Ohio\nRepublican senator, took the oath\nfrom Court Clerk Elmore Cropley,\nthen was escorted to his chair at the\nextreme right of the bench. Asso\nciate Justice William O. Douglas\nshook hands with him and said\n\"Welcome.\u201d\nClark had appeared before the\nCourt previously, both as a practicing\nattorney and as assistant attorney\ngeneral. After Clark\u2019s formal intro\nduction. Mr Truman left the cham\nber. the justices rising.\nHis visit lasted 13 minutes. The\njustices will repeat it soon. They\ntraditionally call at the White House\nduring the first week of a new term.\nALL ITALY EXCEPT\nFEW SMALL AREAS\nWILL BE RELEASED\nAllied Commission Says All\nbut Half Dozen Compart\nments Already Back in Ital\nian Hands\nWashington, Sept 30 \u2014(AP)\u2014 All\nItaly, with the exception of small\nareas along the Yugoslav border, will\nbe turned back to Italian control late\nthis fall by the allied commission.\nThe commission, announcing this\ntoday in connection with the release\nof a report on military government\nin Italy, said that even now all but\na half-dozen compartments in the\nnorth are back in Italian hands.\nThese compartments are Liguria,\nPiemonte, Lombardia, Venezia Triden\ntina, Veneto and part of Venezia\nGiulia. Small portions of some of\nthese compartments will remain under\nallied commission direction for a time\nafter return of the rest of the coun\ntry to the Italians, the announce\nment said.\nIt added that the \u201cpruning down\nof the allied commission, in prep\naration for the day when it will be\ndissolved and Italy will be on her\nown, already ha 3 begun.\u201d The political\nsection of the commission has been\nabolished, with political advice now\nbeing given to the Italians by the\nBritish and American embassies.\nThe extent of Italian participation\nin the war as cobelligerents of the\nallies was disclosed in part.\nItalian navy units\u2014made up from\na fleet of six cruisers, eight destroyers\nand 40 torpedo boats and corvets\nparticipated in more than 000 mis\nsions and helped escort 12.300 ships\nin 1440 convoys. The Italian navy\nswept its own minefields and as\nsigned submarines to run in food and\nsupplies during- the Aegaen opera\ntions.\nThe Italian air force flew 13,400\nsorties. Italian land forces were in\ncombat against Germans as early as\nMarch 31, 1944. The allied-built Ital\nian army and corps of national libera\ntion suffered 22.200 casualties. More\nthan 175.000 Italian service troops\nwere used on allied communications\nlines, in port battalions and in sig\nnal and road maintenance companies.\nTRUMAN READY TO MAKE\nDECISION ON ATOM BOMB\nSpecial Message to Congress\nOn Great Secret Due Some\nTime This Week\nWashington, Oct. I\u2014(AP)\u2014Presi\ndent Truman is about ready to make\nperhaps the gravest decision of his\ncareer\u2014what to do about the atomic\nbomb.\nThe President received this morn\ning from a House appropriations sub\ncommittee a recommendation that\nthe secret be kept until a widely\ndiverse commission looks at all angles.\nHe said he will pass on his own\nIdeas to Congress in a special mes\nsage some time this week.\nOne thing was definitely Indicated\n\u2014that he planned nothing precipitate.\nIt was learned that Senate and\nHouse resolutions for inquiries into\nthe whole subject, which would take\nsome time, stemmed directly from the\nWhite House.\nRain of Cash From Radio City\nHas New Yorkers Mystified\nHandsful of Change Drop On Street From Unidentified\nPhantom Philanthropist\nNew York, Oct. 1 (UP) New\nYorkers crowded around Radio city\u2019s\nInternational building today, gaping\nskyward while coins clipped the pave\nment at their feet like rain from\nheaven.\nNevertheless, there was discontent.\nHome in the crowd thought the\nphilanthropic phantom has turned\nsuddenly stingy. Yesterday the coins\ndropped like hail.\nThe phantom, in ease you haven\u2019t\nheard, has been chucking money out\nthe windows of the International\nbuilding by handsful daily for a week.\nSome days he averaged $lO in nickels\nand dimes. He has the people walk\ning along Fifty-first street almost\nfalling over backward from the cricks\nin their narks as they watch for\ndescending manna.\nBREAKUP OF FEA\nONE OF BROADEST\nIN TRUMAN REGIME\nLeo Crowley\u2019s Resignation\nAccepted by President\nHis Former Jobs to Be\nWidely Distributed\nWashington, Sept. 27 (AP)\nThe resignation of Deo Crowley as\nforeign economic administrator, to\nday marked the end of that agency\nand one of the hroadest governmental\nreshuffles since President Truman\ntook office.\nThe chief executive accepted Crow\nley's resignation effective October 15.\nOnly yesterday the President had in\ndicated that, despite rumors of Crow\nley's intentions, the White House\nwould seek to sew the handsome and\naffable Crowley to his job a little\nlonger.\nThe \u00bbw Lineup\nUnder the reorganization of Crow\nley's former jobs, this' will be the\nlineup:\n1. Administration of the lend-lease\nact, participation of the United States\nin the United Nations relief and re\nhabilitation administration and the\nbuying of certain materials in liber\nated areas, will go to the state de\npartment. These function,, will include\nthe procurement for various foreign\ngovernments of items which these\ngovernments have found it difficult\nto obtain for themselves.\n2. The Rubber Development cor\nporation, the Petroleum Reserves cor\nporation and the United States Com\nmercial company, as well as functions\ndealing with procurement of certain\nstrategic commodities abroad, for\nmerly procured by the United States\nCommercial company independently,\nwill go to the Reconstruction Finance\ncorporation.\n3. Export control, the technical in\ndustrial intelligence committee work\ning now under a directive of the\nUnited States joint chiefs of staff,\nthe facilitation of trade, and the\nfunctions of the clearing of Office for\nForeign Transactions and Reports\nwill go to the commerce department.\n4. The functions of the Office of\nForeign Food Programs and all other\nFEA programs involving food, food\nmachinery and other food facilities,\nwill go to the department of agricul\nture.\nTo unify the disposition of United\nStates foreign property abroad, the\norder made the state department dis\nposal agency of all surplus property,\nexcept certain vessels, in foreign\nareas. The state department also re\nceives the functions relating to over\nseas disposition of property captured\nfrom the enemy, previously a duty\nof the war and navy departments.\nCrowley had fallen heir to several\nhot seats and it was no secret that\nhe was anxious to get off them. He\nhad been the first of this war\u2019s alien\nproperty custodians at a time when\nhe also held his FEA post and his\nposition a.s member of tbe board of\nFederal Deposit Insurance corpora\ntion, in addition to various other\njobs. He quit the alien property job\nshortly after taking on FEA, how\never.\nCrowley was particularly interested\nin his FDIC job. His idea was that\nit should be able to provide Even\nlower costs for bank deposit insur\nance and to return the government's\noriginal capital. This goal, he has\nIndicated, may be reached early next\nyear.\nHis resignation takes him out of\nFDIC too.\nNEGRO MUST DIE\nIN GEORGIA CASE\nFound Guilty in 1942 of\nRaping Member of Own\nRace\u2014White Case \u2018lnflu\nence\u2019 Fought by Lawyers\nAtlanta. Oct. I\u2014(AP)\u2014 After a\nthree-year legal battle, a Negro con\nvicted of raping a member of his own\nrace is under sentence to die Wednes\nday in Georgia's electric chair.\nThe condemned man, Sylvester An\ndrews, was indicted but never tried on\na charge of attempting to ravish\nthree white women, and his counsel\ncontended this influenced the verdict\nand sentence.\nThe trial prosecutor, Solicitor-Gen\neral Charles Garrett, argued, however,\nthat he saw no reason why a Negro\nshould not die for raping a member\nof his own race.\nAndrews was convicted In 1912 in\nMacon, Ga. His conviction has been\ntwice upheld by the Supreme Court.\nHe was resentenced last month.\nHis lawyers asked the state su\npreme court today to consider an ap\nplication for a new\u2019 trial, but the\ncourt refused.\nA member of the state supreme\ncourt, T. Grady Head, as state's at\ntorney-general before his recent ap\npointment to the bench, asked the\nboard of pardons and paroles a few\nmonths ago to spare the Negro\u2019s life.\nHe, too, argued that the charge\nagainst the Negro involving the white\nwomen influenced the conviction and\nsentence.\nThe pardons and parole board re\nfused to intervene.\nTodjiy small boys predominated in\nthe crowd. They were upon the coins\nalmost before they hit.\n\"Those kids are dropping the coins\nthemselves, just to fool us.\u201d a frus\ntrated adult nickel-snatcher shouted.\nThe coins, according to nonproflting\nbystanders, appear to fall In a wild,\nshattered pattern, ns though some\nperson high up in the lowering sky\nscraper had flung a handful of change\nout of the window.\nThe phantom apparently operates\nfrom the 15th. 16th or 18th floors. He\ndoes his tossing between noon and 1\np. m., which would indicate that ho\nwaits until the tenants, many of them\ndoctors and dentists, go to much and\nthen slips Into their empty oiflr.es\nand has his fun.\nTHE SPRINGFIELD WEEKLY REPUBLICAN: SPRINGFIELD, MASS.: THURSDAY, OCTOBER 4, 1945\nTRUMAN ORDERS\nBIG SHAKEUP IN\nAMERICAN NAVY\nFleet Commander-in-Chief\nPosition to Be Abolished\u2014\nImprovements Expected\nFrom Experience Gained\nDuring Wartime\nWashington, Oct. I\u2014(AP)\u2014Presi\ndent Truman has ordered a broad\nreorganization of the navy. The re\nshuffle includes abolition of the po\nsition of commander-in-chief, United\nStates fleet, whose major functions\nare transferred to the chief of naval\noperations.\nKing to Stay for Sow\nSecretary Forrestal has signed a\ndepartmental order, however, con\ntinuing Fleet Admiral Ernest J. King\nin his present position of commander\nof the fleet during a brief period of\ntransition until the new organization\ncontemplated by the President\u2019s or\nder is put into full effect\nKing also continued to hold his\nformal commission as chief of naval\noperations.\nThe order was signed two days ago,\nbut made public only today. A White\nHouse statement said its purpose is\nto enable the navy to incorporate in\nits organization some of the improve\nments which were indicated by war\ntime experience.\n\u201cThese changes are to be made by\nexecutive order,\u201d the statement said,\n\"so that they may be tested for a\nperiod of time before the President\nrecommends to Congress any statu\ntory changes in the organization of\nthe navy.\u201d\nThree Big Divisions\nThe order specifically recognizes\nthat navy business falls into throe\ngrand divisions military matters,\ngeneral and administrative affairs,\nbusiness and related industrial mat\nters.\nThe order requires that the navy\norganization structure \"shall reflect\nthis fundamental division of functions\nand directs the secretary of the navy\nto assign duties among the various\nagencies of the navy accordingly.\"\nThe White House said Secretary\nForrestal has set up an informal\nboard under the chairmanship of Un\ndersecretary Ralph Bard to recom\nmend a specific plan of organization\nbased on the executive order.\nPrincipal powers of the fleet com\nmander-in-chief conferred upon the\nchief of naval operations are the\nduties of \u201cthe principal naval ad\nviser to the President\u201d and \u201ccom\nmand of the operating forces com\nprising the several fleets, seagoing\nforces, sea frontier forces, district and\nother forces, and the related shore\nestablishments.\u201d\nCOMBAT DEATHS\nOF STATE 8734;\n1.5-2 PER CENT\nPreliminary Estimates Put\nMassachusetts Eighth in\nBattle Losses List for Entire\nCountry\nFrom The Republican's\nWashington Bureau\nWashington, Oct. I\u2014Preliminaryl\u2014Preliminary es\ntimates show that about 8734 men\nfrom Massachusetts died in battle or\nas a direct result of combat in this\nglobal war.\nRanking ninth in population, Mas\nsachusetts ranks eighth among the\nstates in order of losses.\nThe percentage of deaths to all men\nfrom Massachusetts mobilized has\nbeen placed at between 1.5 and 2 per\ncent.\n500,000 in Service\nMore than half million men and\nwomen from Massachusetts served in\na military force in which nearly 16,-\n000,000 persons have served. Total\ndeaths from all services are about\n260,000.\nExact figures have not been made\navailable by the war and navy de\npartments and the numbers inducted\ninto the service by states is withheld\nby selective service.\nEstimates can be made on the basis\nof a report as of the first day of this\nyear showing 451,522 persons from\nMassachusetts in service. Total\ndeaths then were 147,933 and of this\nabout 5015 came from Massachusetts\nmen. Of the total deaths, the per\ncentage from Massachusetts was\n.0339.\nCONNALLY URGES\nU.S. KEEP SECRET\nTells VFW at Chicago\nHe Wouldn't Trust Some\nNations With Atomic Bomb\nKnowledge\nChicago, Oct. I\u2014(APl\u2014Chairman\nTom Connally (D-Tex) of the Senate\nforeign relations committee, declared\ntoday that \"we should not divulge\nthe secret\" of the atomic bomb to\nother nations.\nSpeaking at the United Nations\nveterans\u2019 victory conference, curtain\nraiser to the Veterans of Foreign\nWars 46th national encampment,\nConnally said:\n\"We should proceed immediately to\nset up appropriate machinery to\nwork out plans for the control and\nuse of atomic energy. We should\nnot divulge the secret to, other na\ntions.\n\"We found it first It is ours and\nthe world can rest assured that we\nshall never use it except in our own\nnecessary self-defense or in the in\nterest of the peace of the world.\"\nThen, with World war 2 veterans\nfrom 17 nations seated in places of\nhonor, he said \u201cI hope I\u2019m not strik\ning a bum note here\" and added:\n\u201cFrankly, there are nations in the\nworld I wouldn't trust to restrict it\nto those two purposes. We have\nplenty of time to decide and consider\nto whom we will divulge tho secret\nin an appropriate fashion.\"\nAn opposing view was expressed\nby another speaker, Clark M. Elehel\nberger of New York, director of the\nAmerican Association for the United\nNations, who said there must ho \"uni\nversal controls,\" and that \u201cthere are\nreally no atomic secrets except the\nprocesses of industrial manufacture\nand they may not tie secrets very\nlong.\"\nGOP Opens Attack\nOn Tax Slash Plan\n\u2018lt Doesn\u2019t Go Far Enough/ Says Martin Vinson\nWould Cut 5 Billion From Citizens\u2019 Burden, Excuse\n12 Million Payers\nWashington, Oct. I\u2014(AP) \u2014A $5,-\n000,000,000 tax cutting program,\nwhich would relieve 12,000,000 per\nsons of all income taxes starting\nin 1946, and ease the burdens of other\nindividuals and corporations, was pro\nposed to Congress today by the Tru\nman administration.\nFred M. Vinson, secretary of the\ntreasury, carried before the House\nways and means committee the first\nrevenue reduction plan an admin\nistration has sent to Capitol hill in\n16 years.\nIt drew immediate Are from Re\npublicans, whose House leader, Rep\nresentative Martin of Massachusetts,\nsaid:\u2014\n\u201cIt doesn\u2019t go far enough. It\nwon\u2019t open up purchasing power to\nstimulate business and create jobs.\nWe want at least a 20 per cent re\nduction all along the board.\u201d\nAfter a $5,000,000,000 reduction, ac\ncording to Vinson's estimates, rev\nenues in calendar 1946 are expected\nto approximate $27,500,000,000. This\ncompares with a war peak collec\ntion of $46,500,000,000 from taxpayers\nin 1944 and prewar levels of about\n$5,000,000,000.\nVinson proposed:\u2014\n1. Elimination of the 3 per cent\n\"normal\u201d tax on individuals, effec\ntive January 1. This would take\naround 12.000,000 low income per\nsons from the tax rolls completely\nand reduce burdens for all individu\nals by $2,085,000,000, he said. When\nthe war ended there were about 50,-\n000,000 individual income taxpayers.\nThis tax now is assessed against all\nnet income above SSOO without re\ngard to the number of a taxpayer\u2019s\ndependents. Repeal would leave in\nforce the graduated surtaxes under\nwhich the taxpayer is given a SSOO\nFleet With 116 Carriers\nIs Urged by Committee\nHouse Group Unanimously Favors Peacetime Navy of\n1079 Ships\u2014To Cost Billions Annually\nWashington, Sept. 27 (AP) A\npostwar aircraft carrier fleet 16 times\nthe size of America\u2019s flattop forces at\nPearl Harbor time was urged today\nby the House naval affairs committee.\nA resolution was adopted unani\nmously favoring a navy of 1079 com\nbat ships.\nThis force would include 116 car\nriers.\nThe navy had just seven on De\ncember 7, 1941\u2014the Yorktown, Rang\ner, Wasp, Hornet, Lexington, Sara\ntoga and Big-E. the famous Enter\nprise which pulled into Pearl Harbor\nsoon after the Japs had struck.\nEmphasis On Carriers\nThus the emphasis for postwar de\nfense would be on carrier task forces,\njust as the United States offensive in\nthe Pacific was built around that arm\nof attack under Admirals Nimitz, Hal\nsey, Mitscher and McCain.\nThe committee\u2019s findings were in\naccord with the testimony of Secre\ntary of the Navy Forrestal when\nhearings on the postwar fleet opened.\nThe committee suggested the giant\nforce be divided three ways. One\nthird would be fully manned, ready\nto go anywhere. Another third would\nbe tied up but painted, oiled and set\nfor an emergency, the remaining\nthird would be decommissioned.\nSuch a fleet would be the greatest\npeacetime aggregation in history. It\nwould be only 220 fewer combat ves\nsels than the present mighty armada.\nBesides that, all the big punch ships\nwould be of the newest type with\ncrunching fire power.\nWell-Fed U. S. Must Keep\nEurope From Starvation\nEarly Action Likely On Funds for UNRRA\u2014American\nSupplies More Than Ample\nWashington, Sept. 29\u2014(AP) \u2014A pic\nture of European hunger and Ameri\ncan plenty was drawn today by the\nagriculture department in a report\nwhich may presage an administra\ntion drive for early congressional ac\ntion on a recommendation for an ap\npropriation of $1,900,000,000 for for\neign relief.\nThe. report said:\nThe need in continental Europe for\nlarge shipments of foodstuffs from\nother parts of the world in 1945 and\n1946 is acute. In the United States,\ncivilian supplies this fall and winter\nwill be significantly easier than they\nhave been so far in 1945.\nDiscussing the European situation\nin greater detail, the report added:\n\u201cIt is thus plain that only sub\nstantial food imports from outside\nsources can save millions of Europe\nans from near-starvation in the com\ning winter.\u201d\nExtensive aid for Europe from this\ncountry will depend largely upon what\nCongress does about funds for the\nUnited Nations Relief and Rehabilita\ntion administration. Congress has\nmade no move yet to act upon a re\nquest from President Truman, made\nearly this month.\nThe agriculture department has a\nspecial interest in lINRRA recom\nmendation. Sales of food to this\nagency could well provide an outlet\nfor extra food supplies which other\nwise might depress farm prices.\nThe department said this country\ncan easily spare substantial quantities\nof canned meats, some fresh and\nfrozen meats of lower grades, some\nUnion Prevents Broadcast\nOf 'Contented Hour\u2019 Show\nNew York, Oct. I\u2014(AP)\u2014'The Car\nnation \"Contented Hour\" radio pro\ngram was not broadcast aver the\nNational Broadcasting company net\nwork tonight because, the network\nsaid, the American Federation of Mu\nsicians (AFI.) refused to permit its\nmusicians to participate in the pro\ngram.\nArtie Shaw\u2019s band yesterday re\nceived orders not to play on last\nnight's Fitch Bandwagon program\nover the same network\nNBC officials said they had been\nadvised tonight by tho .union that the\nexemption for himself and SSOO for\neach dependent\n2. Repeal the 95 per cent excess\nprofits tax on corporations, which\nVinson said is tolerable only as \u201ca\nmethod for preventing war profiteer\ning.\u201d A check of the ways and\nmeans group Indicated both Demo\ncrats and Republicans favoring re\npeal. Vinson said this would reduce\ncorporate tax burdens by $2,555,-\n000,000.\n3. A sharp reduction in excise\ntaxes, on such things as fur coats,\njewelry, lipstick, admissions and\ntransportation, effective next Julyl.\nMany of the excises would be halved.\nPresent law provides that the high\nexcises written into the 1943 revenue\nact drop automatically to the much\nlower 1942 act levels six months\nafter the official end of the war. Be\ncause of the uncertainty of the ter\nmination date, Vinson proposed next\nJuly. He said this would reduce the\nconsumer tax burden by $547,000,000\nannually.\n4. A temporary freeze of the social\nsecurity tax at the present rate of\n1 per cent against the employers\u2019\npay roll and the employe\u2019s pay en\nvelope, to allow time for an overall\nstudy of proposals for expansion or\nrevision of the social security pro\ngram. Without a freeze the tax\njumps automatically January 1 to\n2.5 per cent against employer and\nemploye.\nRepeal of the \"normal\u201d tax \u2014suc-\ncessor to the war imposed \"victory\u201d\ntax \u2014would remove from the tax\nrolls all childless married men with\nless than SIOOO income; all men with\nwife and one child and income of\nSISOO or less; two children, $2000;\nthree children. $2500 continuing\nwith a SSOO extra exemption for each\ndependent.\nThe committee\u2019s resolution isn\u2019t\nbinding, of course It simply shows\nthe sentiment of that group and\nwould have to be adopted by both\nHouse and Senate before it gains real\nweight. Representative Mott (R-Or),\nranking minority member, wanted to\ngive the resolution the force of law\nbut withdrew his motion and said it\nwas better to simply \"express a\nhope.\"\nSeen as \u201cFixed Goal\u201d\nChairman Vinson (D-Ga) styled the\naction a \"fixed goa!\u201d toward which\nthe committee wants the nation to\nwork.\nVinson estimated the annual cost\nof maintaining a fleet of the size fa\nvored by the committee at between\n$2,500,000,000 and $4,000,000,000.\nThe recommendation called for 116\ncarriers divided this way:\u2014\nThree 45,000-tonners of the Midway\ntype: 24 of the Exeter class, 27,000\ntons; 10 light carriers, 11,000 tons;\n79 escort carriers the baby flat\ntops which proved their worth in\nprotection of convoys.\nThe other ships would include 18\nbattleships, all of the new, tough\nMissouri class; three large cruisers\nwhich are almost as dangerous to\nthe enemy as the biggest battle\nwagon; 31 heavy cruisers, 48 light\ncruisers, 367 destroyers, 296 destroyer\nescorts \u2014the extremely fast and ma\nneuverable convoy duty vessels, 200\nsubmarines. In addition there would\nhave to be hundreds of auxiliaries\noilers, mine layers, patrol ships and\nlanding craft\u2014to support such a\ncombat force.\ncheaper types of canned fish, canned\nand powdered milk, eggs, cheese, po\ntatoes, some dry beans and peas,\ndried fruits, rice, some corn and\nwheat.\nThe administration may press Con\ngress for early decision on the for\neign relief matter for still another\nreason. The agriculture department\ncannot make plans for next year's\nfarm production until it gets a fair\nidea of how much of this year's pro\nduction may be shipped abroad.\nThe domestic food situation was\ndescribed more fully as follows:\nThis fall and winter, the domestic\ncivilian supplies of meats, canned\nfish, canned fruits, fruit juices and\nvegetables, turkey, chicken, dried\nskim milk and dried whole milk,\ncanned milk, fluid cream and potatoes\nwill be materially larger than those\nof recent months and much larger\nthan in the same period last year.\n\u201cIn fact mors potatoes, more eggs,\nand more of the lower grades of beef\nmay be available than civilians will\ndemand at present prices.\"\nA moderate improvement in sup\nplies of butter, cheese, pork, and most\nfats and oils will occur this fall and\nwinter.\nThe sugar situation will improve\nmoderately in the spring if the Cuban\ncrop turns out well, but no substan\ntial increase in world supplies can be\nexpected before early 1947.\nCereal products, except those re\nquiring relatively large quantities of\nfats and sugar, fresh vegetables,\ncitrus fruits, fresh and frozen fish,\nfrozen fruits and vegetables, and fluid\nmilk, will continue plentiful.\naction was taken because two inde\npendently owned stations which\nbroadcast network programs are in\nvolved in disputes with their local\nMusicians\u2019 unions.\nThe stations are WSME in New\nOrleans and WAPO in Chattanooga,\nthey said.\nAn NBC statement said the union\naction in ordering the musicians not\nto play was \"not due to any dispute\nas to wages or working conditions be\ntween either the National Broadcast\ning company or the Carnation com\npany and the American Federation\nof Musicians.\"\nU. S. ARGENTINE\nPOLICY FACING\nEARLY REVIEW\nState Department Comments\nas Southern Nation Con\ntinues Arrests Former\nEmbassador Braden Hints\nAmericas Must Act\nWashington, Sept. 27 (AP)\nThe state department disclosed to\nnight that a general review of\nUnited States policy on Argentina\nis imminent because of recent po\nlitical developments in that coun\ntry.\nBraden Far or* Action\nThe disclosure came In response to\nrequest for comment from Acting\nSecretary Dean Acheson on a talk\nmade by the former embassador to\nArgentina. Spruille Braden. Hastening\nback to this country, Braden said at\na stopover in Puerto RiCo that the\nAmerican nations could not sit idly\nby and watch the course of events\nin Argentina.\nThe regime there had reimposed a\nstate of siege and had caused the\nwholesale arrests of a number of lead\ning citizens.\nThese actions provoked sharp com\nment by several members of the\nUnited States Congress, who advo\ncated the breaking of diplomatic rela\ntions and the imposition of economic\nsanctions.\nThrough a state department spokes\nman. Acheson sent word that, he\nwould have to consult first with Presi\ndent Truman, Secretary of State\nByrnes who is expected in a day or so\nfrom London and with Braden ire\nfore making any statement. After\nthat, he was quoted as saying, when\nthere is any decision it will be an\nnounced.\nBraden, who has been serving as\nembassador to Argentina, now be\ncomes an assistant secretary of state\nin charge of Latin American affairs.\nGoing Under Microscope\n.Acheson\u2019s comment was authorita\ntively interpreted as meaning the\nwhole policy of the United States to\nward Argentina would be put under\nthe microscope to find whether there\nwere any steps which might be taken\nto promote the cause of democracy\nand freedom in that country.\nBraden in San Juan, Puerto Rico,\ntoday declared he was \u201cshocked al\nthough not surprised by developments\nin Argentina.\u201d\nHe described the steps taken by the\nBuenos Aifes government led by Vice-\nPresident Juan Peron. as \u201cextreme\nmeasures of repression\u2019\u2019 against\npatriotic citizens whose sole desire is\nto restore constitutional processes In\ntheir land.\nThe government contended its ac\ntion w\u2019as necessary to prevent inter\nference with forthcoming national\nelections.\nEXCISE TAXES\nWON\u2019T BE CUT\nFOR LONG TIME\nNo Use Waiting for Lower\nRates Before Holidays,\nHouse Indicates\u2014lncome\nTax May Drop\nWashington. Sept 26 (AP)\nPersons delaying purchase of such\nthings as fur coats, jewelry- and lug\ngage in the hope of lower excise taxes\nmay have to wait a long time.\nIn its first action on postwar tax\ncutting, the House ways and means\ncommittee today ruled out any imme\nd.ate reductions in the excise list.\nSome members said the quick ac\ntion is calculated to remove some of\nthe present resistance to the purchase\nof such items prior to the holiday\nbuying season, by putting the con\nsumer on notice that there will be\nno excise cuts soon.\nMeeting for the first time in 16\nyears to consider legislation reduc\ning not raisins taxes, the com\nmittee put its emphasis on cuts In\nindividual and corporation income\nlevies.\nTo Omit Pnblie Hearings\nImpelled by the necessity of getting\na biil on the statute books by No\nvember 1 if 1946 incomes are to be\naffected, the group voted to dispense\nwith public hearings. It invited Sec\nretary of the Treasury Fred M. Van\nson to appear in executive session\nnext week to present the administra\ntion tax-reducing program.\nUnder present law- the high war\ntime excise rates run until six mornhs\nafter the official end of hostilities, as\nproclaimed by the President or by\nCongress. No one knows now when\nthis official termination will come.\nBut six months after the official\nwar end, wjienever it may be. the\nexcise list will revert to the 1942\nrates. This will mean that the levy\non fur coats, jewelry and cosmetics\nwill drop from 20 per cent to 10 (re\ntail); whisky from $9 to $6 a gallon,\nwith similar reductions for other\nitems that tax writers class as luxu\nries.\n701 NAVY SHIPS\nLOST IN THE WAR\n137 First-Line Fighting Ves\nsels Included in Final Ac\ncounting Five Carriers\nPart of War Toll\nWashington. Oct I\u2014(AP)\u2014World\nwar 2 cost the United States navy\n701 vessels.\nA Anal accounting made public to-1\nday by the na'y showed the total in-!\neluded 157 first-line fighting ships.\nThe remainder were auxiliaries and\namphibious craft.\nMajor combatant craft losses In\ncluded two battleships (the Arizona!\nand Oklahoma, both lost at Pearl]\nHarbor): five aircraft carriers, six es-;\ncort, carriers, seven heavy cruisers. 1\nthroe light cruisers. 7! destroyers, ll\ndestoyer-escorts and 52 submarines.\nOther losses included three mine\nlayers. 24 minesweepers. 18 sub\nchasers, 12 gunboats. 15 coast guard\nvessels, three seaplane tenders. 69\nmotor torpedo boats. 41 LSTs. nine\nLSMs. 67 LOTS, 25 LCK six LCSs,\n10 tugs, six tankers. 21 troop trans\nports, 36 district patrol craft. 153\nmiscellaneous district craft, four\ncargo vessels and 22 miscellaneous\nnr mn_\n13 of 162 GAR Veterans\nAttend Convention in Ohio\nWomen Run 79th General Encampment While Old Sol\ndiers Talk in Hotel Lobby\nBRITAIN MAY GET\nEASY TERMS ON\n5-BILLION LOAN\nMajor Concessions Likely in\nBasic U. S. Foreign Loan\nPolicy\u2014France and Soviet\nto Pay Higher Rate\nWashington, Sept. 27\u2014LAP)\u2014The\nUnited States probably will propose\nto make substantial concessions in its\nbasic foreign loan policy in order to\nmeet British requests for financial aid\non a. grand scale.\nThis was strongly indicated today\nby officials familiar with Anglo-\nAmerican economic negotiations They\nview the loan problem as the heart\nof future trade relations between the\nworld\u2019s two greatest commercial\npowers.\nAt the moment official opinion fa\nvors recommending to Congress a\n$5,000,900,000 loan with a very low\nrate of interest and no restrictions\non where the money could be spent.\nThis is about $2,000,000,000 more\nthan the minimum which the British\nhave discussed. (Their maximum fig\nure has been about 56,000,000,000.) It\nalso is some $2,000,000,000 more than\nAmerican negotiators had in mind a\nfew weeks ago. The purpose in rais\ning the estimate, which is still tenta\ntive. is to try to place the British in\na financial position so sound that\ntheir credit with other nations wall\nbe strengthened. The theory is that\nwith more American credit they may\nactually have to use less of the Amer\nican money than might be necessary\nif they got a sum that offered no\nmargin over their bare necessities.\nThe concessions in the loan policy\nmay result in sharp distinctions be\ntween what the British get and what\nthe French and Russians, for exam\nple, get from the United States.\nThe French want at least $2,009,-\n000,000 over the next three years or\nso and the Russians over their period\nof reconstruction would like to obtain\n56,000.000.000 from this country. Pres\nent official thought runs to the idea\nof charging the French and Russians\n\"reasonable\u201d interest on the money\nthey obtain here and restricting the\nfunds to expenditure in this country.\nThe reasons are, first, that both\nRussia and France have considerable\nresources with which to make repay\nment over the 30 or 40-year period\nand. second, they need the money for\ncapital goods purposes for reconstruc\ntion.\nA study of the information pre\nsented by the British here in almost\nthree weeks of negotiations evidently\nhas convinced United States officials\nthat the British have very inadequate\npayment resources so that the in\nterest charged them should be at a\nminimum. Also apparently adopted is\nthe idea that they need an opportuni\nty to buy in many countries in order\nto solve their problem which is one\nof existence while they rebuild their\nimport and export trades\nThe turnover of official thinking on\nj British loan prospects strongly em\nphasizes that the British appeal for\nj a grant, free of cost, has fallen on\ndeaf ears here. Furthermore these,\nsame authorities say there is no pros\npect for what they call \"a trick set\ntlement\u2019\u2019 on tile British needs either\nby drawing on the gold hoard at Fort\nKnox. Ky., or by declaring ler.d-lease\nretroactive and paving back to Brit\nain several billions spent in this coun\ntry before iend-iease began.\nJOB SHORTAGE\nMAY LAST YEAR\nReconversion Director Says\n8 Million to Be Unemployed\nby Spring but Future Still\nLooks Hopeful\nWashington, Oct- I\u2014(APT\u2014High\nunemployment will \u201cpersist through\n1946,'' Reconversion Director John W.\nSnyder predicted today.\nSnyder previously had forecast that\n5.000,000 may be out of work by\nspring Reiterating that estimate to\nday. he said that while he is firmly\noptimistic\u201d about the future, he con\nsiders a period of large-scale job\nlessness inevitable because:\n1. \u201cIt takes time for industry to\nturn around\u2014to stop work on muni\ntions and retool for work on peace\ntime products/*\n2. It will be impossible to find\njobs at the proposed million-a-month\ndemobilization rate.\nSnyder's forecasts were made in a\n46-page report to the President and\nCongress He called it \u201cthree keys\nto reconversion production, jobs,\nmarkets.\u201d\nHe cautions:\n1. The nation must work together\nas a team.\n2. Labor management difficulties\nmust be settled promptly.\n3. Congress should adopt promptly\na four-point program suggested by\nPresident Truman. This calls for\n\u201cfull employment, transitional tax\nadjustments, broadening and raising\nunemployment compensation and\nraising minimum wages/*\n4. The executive branch must be\nas \u201cvigorous** in peace as it was in\nSingle World Government\nBesought by 39 Americans\nThey \u2018Desperately\u2019 Urge President Truman to Take Im\nmediate Steps, Citing Atomic Power\nNew York Sept. 27\u2014(AP) \u2014Thirty\ni nine Americans told President Tru\nj man today that a single, democratic\ngovernment for all mankind w as the\nonly means of controling the world\nj\u00bbide pow er supplied by the atomic\nj bomb.\nIn an open letter, they \"earnestly\nland even desperately\" urged him to\ntake immediate steps to initiate a\nworld government, declaring that dis\ncovery of atomic power had made the\npeoples of the world ready for \"a\ntrue constitutional convention.\"\nLet\u2019s Have a \u201cBig One\"\n\"Let us be done with big threes\nand big fours and big fives.\" they\nurged. \u201cLet us have the big one.\none government for all mankind, re\nsponsible directly to all mankind, con\ncerned tor all mankind, quick to pro\ntect all mankind from evil, whether\nmV\n7\nNATIONAL\nColumbus. 0., Oct. I\u2014(UP)\u2014Th*1 \u2014(UP) \u2014Th*\nGrand Army of the Republic op*n\u00abd\nits 79t.h general encampment here\ntoday with only 13 of its surviving\n162 veterans in attendance.\nTheir meeting lacked the action of\nan American I-eg ion convention but\nthe Civil war veterans made up for\nit with an enthusiasm that belied\ntheir average age of 99.\nTypical of the group was Robert\nM. Rownd, 101. of Ripley. N. Y. Ha\nled several of his buddies in a gen\neral kidding of Frederick Pfeisterof\nCincinnati who entered the veterans'\nfirst, executive council meeting sport\ning two black eyes.\nPfeister, 99 slipped as he was\ntaking hi 3 bath last night\u2014he said.\nHis buddies grinned and winked.\nThey laughed a lot, posed for. pic\ntures aa.l L showing their\nability to get around without as\nsistance. They let the women-folk*\nrun the show Hundreds of dele\ngates to the women's various affili\nated organizations milled about, at\ntending meetings and listening to\nspeeches.\nBut it was none of that for the\nreal stars of the show. They lounged\nin the hotel lobby and talked over\nold times, politics, the state of their\nhealth and the war just ended.\nMany a downy-cheeked veteran of\nOkinawa or the Ardennes forest was\nbutton-holed and told how U. S.\nGrant would have done it.\nConvoyed by their nurses and rela\ntives, the doughty 13 banqueted at\nMemorial hall tonight and listened to\nwelcoming speeches from Gov\nFrank J. Lausche of Ohio and Mayor\nJames A. Rhodes of Columbus.\nReturning Commander in Chief\nIsaac W. Sharpe of Warsaw, Ind.,\n97. and one of \u201che youngest present,\nacknowledged the welcomes.\nWilliam H. Osborn. 102, of Joplm,\nMo., appeared to have an edge in\nthe campaign for commander-in-chief\nalthough he said he didn\u2019t care\nwhether he won it or not.\n\u2022T\u2019ve been nominated three times\nbefore for commander-ln-chief,\u201d he\nsaid. \u201cSomebody else can have It.\nIt\u2019s too much sugar for a penny. The\ncommander doesn\u2019t have much to do\nwith the GAR any more\u2014the women\nrun it. to suit themselves.\u201d\nDEMOCRATSWIN\nPOWER AGAIN IN\nNORWALK VOTE\nE. J. Kelley Named Mayor\nAfter Two Years of GOP\u2014\nAnnual Legislature Sessions\nFavored\nNew Haven. Ct.. Oct. 1 (AP)\nNorwalk, biggest prize at stake, re\nturned to the Democratic fold today\nin municipal electiona in Connecticut\nwhich saw Republicans lose ground\nin another urban area but maintain\ntheir traditional dominance in rural\nterritory.\nOusted from power two years ago\nfor the first time in a decade, Demo\ncrats bounced back into the victory\ncolumn in Norwalk by winning the\ncity mayoralty. The poet went to sos\nmer Senator Edward J. Kelley.\nHonors were divided in the other\ntwo cities which elected mayor, Demo\ncrats strengthening their grip onTor\nrington and Republicans wanning\nagain in Bristol.\nThe Torrington mayoralty went to\nWilliam A. Kilmartin. Democrat, while\nMayor Daniel Davis, Republican, was\nreeiected in Bristol for his third two\nyear term.\nThe other 13S communities which\nballoted, most of them in small ru\nral areas long dominated by Republi\ncans, elected official families headed\nby boards of selectmen.\nReturns from early reporting com\nmunities showed most of them in fa\nvor of three proposed amendments to\nthe state constitution. Chief among\nthe proposals was one calling for an\nnual rather than biennial sessions of\nthe Legislature.\nThe other constitutional changes\nproposed would increase the salary\nof jtaie legislators from S3OO to S6OO\nfor their two-year term and provide\nfor the 'ieutenant-governor-e!ect to\nbecome governor should the governor\nelect be unable to assume office.\nKelley won the mayoralty m Nor\nwalk the largest community to ballot,\nby nearly 1200 votes, thus wiping out\na 3000-vote victory margin achieved\nby Republicans two years ago. The\n'cat manufactur.ng center of 40,000\ngave Kelley an unofficial total of\n7537 votes again 6351 for his Repub\nlican rival Raynor Werme.\nKelley succeeds Mayor B. Oliver,\nRepublican, who did not seek reelec\ntion.\nPRESIDENT ASKED\nTO AID HAZEL SCOTT\nWash ngton, Oct I\u2014(AP)\u2014Repre\nsentative A Jam C. Powell, Jr., Negro\nDemocrat from New York city, asked\nPresident Truman today to take \"im\nmediate action\u201d on what he called\nthe barring of his wife. Pianist Hazel\nRcott. from a proposed concert in\nConstitution halL The hall is owned\nby the Daughters of the American\nRevolution.\nIn 1939 Marian Anderson. Negro\ncontralto, wts barred from Constitu\ntion oa.l. She later sang to a crowd\nof 75.000 at the Lincoln Memorial\nplaza.\nOwen J Roberts, former Supreme\nCourt justice, w-as one of the signers\nof the letter, released by the Federal\nWorld Government. Inc. Other sign\ners included Christopher Morley. au\nthor; Right Rev G. Ashton Oldham.\nProtestant Episcopal bishop of Al-\nI bany Strlngfellow Barr, president of\nst John's college. Annapolis, Md.;\nMary Roberts Rinehart, author:\nGeorge S. Kaufman, playwright, and\n1 Raymond Swing, radio commentator.\nThe letter said the proposed world\ngovernment should be federal in\ncharacter and not a completely uni\nfied world state \u201cbecause our local\nnational governments still command\nour loyalties, and because we are so\ndifferent in many ways.\"\n\"It should have only expressly\ngranted powers, leaving all others to\nthe national government and to the\npeople,\" the letter said.","height":"25978","width":"19370"}}
